"""Classification and relationships for the 1011 distinct definition-gap
words examples/README.md's "Adding a stable entry_id" work surfaced next:
every word already in the 838-word Common Vocabulary Cache has its own
`definition` text; breaking every one of those down into its own words
(the same Word.definition_words() approach definition_gap_vocabulary.py
already used for the Physics Domain, 4.4) found 1011 distinct words with
no entry anywhere in Common itself. Classifying and relating them surfaced
152 more: 129 base lemmas a derived form's own definition named (e.g.
"denotes" -> "Third person singular of denote") but that, on inspection,
were missing too, and 23 second, homograph senses an existing lexical_form
needed once its zero-derivation VERB or NOUN sense turned out to be the one
a relationship actually pointed at (e.g. "mark" existed only as a NOUN, but
"marked"/"marking"/"marks" are plainly VERB forms) -- the same "found while
relating the new words" extension pattern common_core_vocabulary.py's bonus
NOMINALISATION nouns and this file's own base lemmas both already establish.
1163 words classified in total, every one destined for the Common
Vocabulary Cache (every Domain inherits them, not just one) since none of
them are remotely domain-specific -- ordinary general-English vocabulary,
exactly the words a dictionary's own definitions lean on constantly. Only
1158 of those are open-class and appear below in WORD_ENTRIES, seeded via
WordSeeder.promote_word -- the promoted-words path. The remaining 5 turned
out not to fit that path at all, once seeding actually rejected them: "non"
and "semi" are bound prefixes (PartOfSpeech.OTHER), and OTHER is
deliberately never seeded anywhere in this cache (word_seeder.py's own
comment: "being able to articulate a real definition for a word is
evidence it belongs in NOUN/VERB/whatever, not OTHER") -- excluded outright,
not forced in. "concerning"/"including" (PREPOSITION) and "themself"
(PRONOUN) are genuine closed-class words, but promoted_words.json is
open-class only (WordSeeder.OPEN_CLASSES); common_definition_gap_vocabulary_seeding.py's
own add_mandatory_entries() hand-adds these three directly to
prepositions.json/pronouns.json instead, the same "closed class needs its
own file, not promoted_words.json" discipline common_core_vocabulary_seeding.py's
add_metalinguistic_entries() already established for supplementary (not
mandatory) files -- these three are the first genuinely mandatory
closed-class additions found this way.

WORD_ENTRIES is a *list* of (lexical_form, part_of_speech, domain,
definition) tuples, not the Dict[str, Tuple[str, str, str]] the other
classification files in this directory use -- deliberately, since a Dict
keyed by lexical_form alone cannot represent two entries sharing one
lexical_form under different parts of speech (the 23 homograph senses),
the same reason promoted_words.json itself is keyed by
(lexical_form, part_of_speech), not lexical_form alone (WordSeeder,
asset_version 1.13.0). domain is always "common" here -- unlike
definition_gap_vocabulary.py, this batch never had a "physics" placement
to weigh, since it was drawn from Common's own definitions; "exclude" was
decided post hoc for non/semi once promotion itself rejected them (see
above), not up front, and neither appears below any more (removed rather
than kept as a documented no-op). None of the 1011 original candidates
were tokenizer artefacts (those -- digits from numeral definitions,
"e"/"g" from "e.g.", the "s" of a possessive -- were filtered out before
this file was even drafted).

MORPHOLOGICAL_LINKS is (base_lexical_form, base_part_of_speech,
relationship_kind, derived_lexical_form) -- base_part_of_speech is always
given explicitly, even where the base has only one sense, because five
bases here (cause, form, name, point, state) are pre-existing Common
homographs (NOUN and VERB both), and resolving one of those by lexical
form alone would silently attach to the wrong sense -- the exact bug
RelationshipSeeder itself was fixed for (relationships/README.md,
asset_version 1.8.0). The base may be an existing Common word, another word
in this same batch, or one of the 23 homograph senses above; the seeding
script resolves all three the same way. Two derivations found by pattern-
matching every definition's own "Past participle of X"/"Plural of X"/etc.
phrasing were deliberately dropped: "proportion" (a false positive -- its
definition uses the word "comparative" descriptively, not as a claim that
proportion IS the comparative form of "relation") and "singles" -> "single"
(too idiomatic/marginal a VERB sense of "single" -- "to single out" -- to
justify minting a fourth homograph sense for one relationship).
Every reverse LEMMA_FORM edge (or the enum's own more specific inverse,
where one exists) is materialised too when seeded, the Common relationship
cache's own established convention.
"""

